<TITLE> July-Oct sees 21pc rise in remittance </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 3 (bdnews24.com) Bangladeshi workers overseas remitted over $3.6 billion in the first four months of the fiscal year, while the Bangladesh Bank chief sounding a warning bell on inflation. The Forex Reserve and Treasury Management Department of the central bank said the remittance was 21.23 percent higher than the same period last year, which was $2.9 billion. The total foreign currency reserves had jumped to $9.6 billion, as of Tuesday, following October's remittance inflow of $911.2 million. Bangladesh Bank governor Atiur Rahman said the global economic meltdown was not affecting continued high remittance. He hoped that the recessionary situation would not affect it in the future. He told bdnews24.com, "This flow is a very good sign for our economy." "But now we have to ensure investment in productive sectors at any cost. If not, inflation might rise," he added. September saw $887.6 million in remittance, while an all-time record for monthly remittance was set in August, at $937.9 million. The first month of the quarter, July, saw $886.4 million. Bangladesh saw $9.7 billion in remittance in 2008-09, and $7.9 billion in 2007-08. The World Bank, International Monetary Fund and the Asian Development Bank had all warned last year of collapsing remittance due to the global downturn remittance. Local economists were also concerned about overseas labour markets shrinking. Currently, some 6.5 million Bangladeshis are living and working overseas. Around 0.35 million people went abroad for work in the first seven months (Jan-Aug) of the calendar year, according to the overseas employment ministry. bdn
